"Schreiber A., Zapp P., Markewitz P., Vögele S.","Environmental analysis of a German strategy for carbon capture and storage of coal power plants",2010,"Energy Policy","38","12",,"7873","7883",,,10.1016/j.enpol.2010.09.006,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-78549294471&partnerID=40&md5=d4f07b1f6aca24b1b0a0d40a007312ba","Inst. of Energy Research-Systems Analysis and Technology Evaluation (IEF-STE), Forschungszentrum Jülich GmbH, 52425 Jülich, Germany","Schreiber, A., Inst. of Energy Research-Systems Analysis and Technology Evaluation (IEF-STE), Forschungszentrum Jülich GmbH, 52425 Jülich, Germany; Zapp, P., Inst. of Energy Research-Systems Analysis and Technology Evaluation (IEF-STE), Forschungszentrum Jülich GmbH, 52425 Jülich, Germany; Markewitz, P., Inst. of Energy Research-Systems Analysis and Technology Evaluation (IEF-STE), Forschungszentrum Jülich GmbH, 52425 Jülich, Germany; Vögele, S., Inst. of Energy Research-Systems Analysis and Technology Evaluation (IEF-STE), Forschungszentrum Jülich GmbH, 52425 Jülich, Germany","This paper combines an existing projection of the development of electricity production with a technology-specific environmental assessment. The combination of these two approaches, which so far have only been performed separately, allows a discussion about environmental effects of carbon capture and storage (CCS) implementation strategies on a national level. The results identify the future role of lignite and hard coal in German power production. The implementation of CCS technology leads to a considerable loss of efficiency. Due to CCS, about 50 million t of lignite will be additionally required in 2030 in comparison to the reference case without CCS in 2010. Increasing demand, the replacement of old plants and the compensation of efficiency losses lead to highly ambitious expansion rates. In the case of CCS implementation, the global warming potential (GWP) can be reduced by up to 70%. However, other environmental impacts increase in part considerably. Compliance with national ceilings for NO x emissions can only be reached by compensation measures in other sectors. The results of the environmental assessment demonstrate the significant role of the coal composition, coal origin and the required transport. CO 2 pipeline transport and CO 2 storage make a fairly minor contribution to the overall environmental impact. © 2010 Elsevier Ltd.","Coal-fired power plants with CCS; Energy scenario; Life cycle assessment","Carbon capture and storage; Coal composition; Coal power plants; Coal-fired power plant; Compensation measures; Efficiency loss; Electricity production; Energy scenario; Environmental analysis; Environmental assessment; Environmental effects; Expansion rate; German Power productions; Global warming potential; Hard coal; Implementation strategies; Life cycle assessment; National level; Old plants; Pipeline transport; Technology leads; Coal fueled furnaces; Coal industry; Coal storage; Environmental impact assessments; Fossil fuel power plants; Global warming; Life cycle; Lignite; Environmental impact; carbon dioxide; carbon sequestration; coal-fired power plant; electricity generation; environmental assessment; environmental impact; global warming; life cycle analysis; lignite; nitrogen oxides; Germany",,,,,,"Bauer, C., Heck, T., Dones, R., Mayer-Spohn, O., Blesl, M., (2009), NEEDS (New Energy Externalities Developments for Sustainability). Final report on technical data, costs, and life cycle inventories of advanced fossil power generation systems. Paul Scherrer Institut (PSI) und Institut für Energiewirtschaft und Rationelle Energieanwendung, University of Stuttgart (IER)(2004), 13. BImSCHV, Ordinance of large combustion plants and gas turbine plants, 20 July 2004, Federal Law Gazette I, p. 1717, Bundesanzeigerverlag, Köln(2008), BDEW, Energiewirtschaftliches Institut Köln/EEFA. Energiewirtschaftliches Gesamtkonzept 2030. Studie im Auftrag des Bundesverbandes der Energie- und Wa